    {
      "para_id": "p32",
      "section_id": "s2",
      "section_path": [
        "Algorithmic Pluralism"
      ],
      "ordinal": 32,
      "text": "Digital fairness by design should be at the core of the EU's Digital Fairness Act not only because it is an overarching answer to the questions posed by the DFA's call for evidence but because digital fairness naturally aligns with the EU Charter of Fundamental Rights and the EU's Digital Services Act.",
      "char_len": 303,
      "chunk_word_count": 52,
      "ratios": {
        "alpha": 0.9841269841269841,
        "digit": 0.0,
        "non_space": 0.8316831683168316
      },
      "meaning": {
        "score": 0.9880952380952381,
        "flags": []
      },
      "selection": {
        "selected": true,
        "policy": "threshold+top_k"
      },
      "chunk_quality": "ok"
    },
    {
      "para_id": "p33",
      "section_id": "s2",
      "section_path": [
        "Algorithmic Pluralism"
      ],
      "ordinal": 33,
      "text": "Safety by design is also a core element of CCDH's blueprint for a revised social media sphere – the STAR Framework. Integrating fairness and safety into the design of technology products and social media platforms means prioritizing user health, well-being, human rights and civil liberties. This can only be done by meaningfully changing the operational logic of online platforms – hence the need for algorithmic pluralism.",
      "char_len": 424,
      "chunk_word_count": 64,
      "ratios": {
        "alpha": 0.9749303621169917,
        "digit": 0.0,
        "non_space": 0.8466981132075472
      },
      "meaning": {
        "score": 0.9811977715877438,
        "flags": []
      },
      "selection": {
        "selected": true,
        "policy": "threshold+top_k"
      },
      "chunk_quality": "ok"
    },
    {
      "para_id": "p34",
      "section_id": "s2",
      "section_path": [
        "Algorithmic Pluralism"
      ],
      "ordinal": 34,
      "text": "The EU has tried, through Article 27 of the Digital Services Act (DSA), to create a regulatory instrument that governs the use of recommender systems on VLOPs. Article 27 mandates that providers of online platforms \"set out in their terms and conditions the main parameters used in their recommendation systems and any options for the recipient of the service to modify or influence those parameters\".[3] Article 27 is aimed at increasing the transparency of recommender systems but it fails to inform users about platforms' rules of engagement or, even, to meaningfully change these parameters if users are unhappy with them. While transparency is an important first step to understanding algorithms, the Digital Fairness Act is a crucial opportunity to embed real algorithmic choice in the EU's digital legislation.",
      "char_len": 817,
      "chunk_word_count": 129,
      "ratios": {
        "alpha": 0.9652173913043478,
        "digit": 0.010144927536231883,
        "non_space": 0.8445532435740514
      },
      "meaning": {
        "score": 0.9739130434782609,
        "flags": []
      },
      "selection": {
        "selected": true,
        "policy": "threshold+top_k"
      },
      "chunk_quality": "ok"
    },
    {
      "para_id": "p35",
      "section_id": "s2",
      "section_path": [
        "Algorithmic Pluralism"
      ],
      "ordinal": 35,
      "text": "Additionally, algorithmic pluralism would be a helpful tool to further the DSA's aim to protect minors online. Child-specific algorithms could easily be used to show only age-appropriate content to underage users or parameters can be changed to protect children from personalized recommendations. Platforms already doing this for their DSA compliance would be one step ahead in offering algorithmic choice to their users.",
      "char_len": 421,
      "chunk_word_count": 62,
      "ratios": {
        "alpha": 0.9805555555555555,
        "digit": 0.0,
        "non_space": 0.8551068883610451
      },
      "meaning": {
        "score": 0.9854166666666667,
        "flags": []
      },
      "selection": {
        "selected": true,
        "policy": "threshold+top_k"
      },
      "chunk_quality": "ok"
    },
    {
      "para_id": "p36",
      "section_id": "s3",
      "section_path": [
        "Algorithmic Pluralism",
        "Conclusion"
      ],
      "ordinal": 36,
      "text": "The Digital Fairness Act's stated aims of addressing addictive design, dark patterns and making the digital world a more just place for consumers are noble in scope. Algorithmic pluralism is a bold way of fulfilling these policy goals and, ultimately, of putting European consumers first.",
      "char_len": 288,
      "chunk_word_count": 45,
      "ratios": {
        "alpha": 0.9754098360655737,
        "digit": 0.0,
        "non_space": 0.8472222222222222
